  "articleSummary": "This technical analysis argues that adding engineers to accelerate software delivery is a mathematical fallacy, as team expansion exponentially increases communication overhead and coordination costs. Citing Brooks’ Law and empirical research, the author details how onboarding delays, mentorship taxes, and context loss negate productivity gains, even when leveraging modern tools like CI/CD pipelines, microservices, and async communication frameworks. Targeted at engineering managers and technical leaders, the piece maintains a data-driven, cautionary tone and relies on recurring mathematical framing (n(n-1)/2, O(n²)) alongside metaphors like the \"coordination tax\" and \"archaeological digs\" to advocate for smaller, autonomous teams.",
